Should the public excitement for this change spread into more hearts and minds, legal changes that will make abortion easier and more readily available uninterruptedly until 12 weeks will become inevitable. This alarm od delay coupled with health care shortages and declining loads of male population will result in shortage of female medical professionals, especially the ones capable of carrying out abortion works. This unavoidable shortage of medical professionals skilled in abortion practice will automatically provide incentives for law reforms. Specifically if those women that do not have access to termination in the second trimester face greater scrutiny on health grounds, they will start raising alarm to their government representatives. This plebeian “Pressure from below” will eventually force the government to “legislate from above”.

Political and legal culture of a society largely determines the fate of its women. Specifically, in the context of women’s rights, where there is a will, there is a way. Just like in the Republic of Serbia, where the religious faction and those professionals who literally earn their living off abortion have fairly culted power position (other than in the Brithish Parliament, where abortion is legal until the ninth month) these sides will be ready to explode into a rage when confronted with even the slightest reforms (…) (as in the case of Serbia). However, regarding the abortion laws, these constant, anti-popular (but popularistic) strivings from above, are but a mere legislative mirage which serves purely to mislead and soften public opinion.
